  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Bankconvenant - Counterpart FNV</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This proposal concerns the financing modality for funding for the deployment and work of signatory NGOs and unions for the implementation of the IMVO Covenant for the banking sector. This commitment of social organizations aims to ensure continuity of qualitativeinput and to make it possible to continuously learn from each other in the implementation of this covenant, and to exchange the scholarship between covenant processes.
This proposal has been established in a series of talks between the Ministry of Foreign Affairsand Oxfam Novib. FNV will participate in all activities related to the implementation of the Bank convenant and specifically, the development of an HR risk matrix and value chain mapping.</narrative>
  </description>
  <participating-org role="4" type="90">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">FNV Federatie Nederlandse Vakbeweging</narrative>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The FNV is the largest trade union confederation in the Netherlands. It was formed through the merging in 1976 of the Netherlands Federation of Trade Unions (NVV) and the Catholic Federation of Dutch Trade Unions (NKV), the formal process being completedin 1982.

As early as the 1960s, it had been realized that a more firmly knit bond between the then three existing confederations (NVV, NKV and CNV, the Christian Trade Union Federation) was necessary for the purposes of united negotiations at industrylevel and sometimes at enterprise level. The ultimate formation of one united confederation proved difficult, however, among other things because the existing three were still too closely linked to other organizations (political parties) of the same (denominational) character, plus the fact that their mutual ideological differences were still very great. In the event, the NVV and NKV merged to form the new FNV confederation, while the CNV continued as a separate one. There are 18 unions affiliated to theFNV, with over a million members in all.Its membership likewise stood at just over a million in 1980, but then dropped over the following ten years to around 900,000; after 1990 it rose to just over the million mark once again.</narrative>
  </participating-org>
